'''Christopher F. Egan''' is an [[United States|American]] businessman, fundraiser, diplomat and philanthropist.  Egan served as [[United States Ambassador to the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD) in Paris, France from October 2007 to November 2009. He was appointed by President George W. Bush and was confirmed by the U.S. Senate on October 26, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/96406.htm|title=Christopher F. Egan|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=2007-12-05|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref>

==Biography==

===Early life===
Egan was born in [[Boston, Massachusetts]] to Maureen and [[Richard Egan (businessman)|Richard Egan]], the co-founder of the [[EMC Corporation]]. He graduated from [[Xaverian Brothers High School]] in [[Westwood, Massachusetts]] in 1982.  He then received a bachelor of science in electrical engineering from the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]] in 1986 and a master of public administration with a concentration in leadership from the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/96406.htm|title=Christopher F. Egan|publisher=[[U.S. Department of State]]|date=2007-12-05|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref>

===Career=== 
Egan is the President and a founding member of Carruth Capital, LLC, based in [[Westborough, Massachusetts]].  Carruth Capital, founded in 1994, is one of New England's top 10 commercial real estate investment and development firms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbjournal.com/article/20131209/PRINTEDITION/312079970/christopher-egan-president-carruth-capital-westborough|title=2013 Power Player - Christopher Egan: President, Carruth Capital, Westborough|publisher=Worcester Business Journal|date=2013-12-09|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref>

In 2004, Egan produced a critically acclaimed documentary entitled, ''Eclipsed by the Sun: The Political Education of John Kerry'', a documentary about John Kerry's unsuccessful 1972 campaign for the Massachusetts' 5th Congressional district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angelfire.com/bc3/sully/|title=Eclipsed by the Sun: The Political Education of John Kerry|publisher=Egan Productions, LLC|date=2004-07-04|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref>  Egan was a [[Bush Pioneer|Bush Ranger]] following his significant fundraising for the [[George W. Bush presidential campaign, 2004]] and the [[John McCain presidential campaign, 2008]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/030/000173508/|title=NNDB: Christopher F. Egan|publisher=NNDB|date=2015-05-15|accessdate=2015-05-15}}</ref>

From October 2007 to January 2009, Egan served as ambassador to the Paris-based [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] (OECD). He was appointed by President George W. Bush and was confirmed by the U.S. Senate on October 26, 2007.  According to Egan, he was tasked with reducing the U.S. investment in the organization while making sure other countries paid more of the budget.  According to Egan, "I had to convince 29 other countries that they should pay more" and that he succeeded for the first time in history to reduce the U.S. contribution to an international organization at the same time that the its budget went up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbjournal.com/article/20100329/METROWEST01/303299960/a-diplomatic-approach--christopher-egan-president-carruth-capital|title=10 To Watch: A Diplomatic Approach - Christopher Egan, President, Carruth Capital|publisher=Worcester Business Journal|date=2012-03-23|accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>

On March 18, 2015, Egan became the Chairman of the Board of Directors for [[The Home for Little Wanderers]], the nation<U+2019>s oldest and one of New England<U+2019>s largest child and family service agencies.  In addition, Egan and his wife, Jean, founded and direct "Break the Cycle of Poverty," a non-profit foundation dedicated to lifting families out of poverty through education. The foundation works to teach economically challenged individuals and families the skills needed to break free of poverty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehome.org/site/News2?page=NewsArticle&id=9690#.VVftVDY4mko|title=Christopher F. Egan Named Board Chair|publisher=[[The Home for Little Wanderers]]|date=2015-03-18|accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref> He is also a trustee of the Egan Family Foundation.

===Personal===
Egan and his wife, Jean, have four children and live in [[Boston, Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wbjournal.com/article/20100329/METROWEST01/303299960/a-diplomatic-approach--christopher-egan-president-carruth-capital|title=10 To Watch: A Diplomatic Approach - Christopher Egan, President, Carruth Capital|publisher=Worcester Business Journal|date=2012-03-23|accessdate=2015-05-16}}</ref>

